{
  "text": "Scalar timing theory is a mathematical model that describes formal properties of the cognitive processes that may operate when an individual achieves a variety of temporal discriminations [CITATION_1] . This analysis has successfully accounted for more than 97% of the variance in behavior of both rats and pigeons in several different timing tasks. It has also led to the development of a set of experimental procedures that can be used to separate the different psychological processes involved in timing. In the basic discrete-trial fixed-interval (FI) procedure, each trial begins with a signal onset. The animal is free to respond at any time during the signal, but only the first response after the fixed duration is reinforced. The peak-interval (PI) procedure, a variation of the FI procedure, provides independent measures of several processes involved in temporal discriminations.",
  "citation_candidates": [
